1. What is a Data Type?

A data type tells JavaScript what kind of value is being stored and how that value should be handled.

let age = 23;        // Number
let name = "Piyush"; // String
let isPlaced = true; // Boolean

JavaScript is a dynamically typed language, which means a variable can hold different types of values at different times.

let x = 10;      // Number
x = "Hello";     // String
x = true;        // Boolean
2. Categories of Data Types

JavaScript data types are divided into two categories:

Data Types
    |
    +---- Primitive
    |
    +---- Non-Primitive (Reference)
3. Primitive Data Types

Primitive values are:

Immutable
Stored by value
Usually stored directly in stack memory

There are 7 primitive data types.

Data Type	Example
Number	10, 20.5
String	"Hello"
Boolean	true, false
Undefined	undefined
Null	null
BigInt	123n
Symbol	Symbol()
A. Number

JavaScript has only one numeric type.

let a = 10;
let b = 20.5;
let c = -100;

Unlike Java:

int a = 10;
double b = 20.5;

JavaScript internally stores all normal numbers as 64-bit floating point values (IEEE-754).

console.log(typeof 10);     // number
console.log(typeof 20.5);   // number
B. String

Strings represent text.

let name = "Piyush";
let city = 'Jaipur';
let msg = `Hello`;

Strings are immutable.

let s = "Hello";

s[0] = 'Y';

console.log(s); // Hello
C. Boolean

Represents logical values.

let isStudent = true;
let isPlaced = false;
D. Undefined

A variable declared but not assigned.

let x;

console.log(x); // undefined
E. Null

Represents intentional absence of value.

let user = null;

Funny JavaScript behavior:

console.log(typeof null);

Output:

"object"

This is a historical bug in JavaScript.

F. BigInt

Used for very large integers.

let x = 123456789012345678901234567890n;

Example:

console.log(typeof x);
// bigint
G. Symbol

Creates unique values.

let id1 = Symbol("id");
let id2 = Symbol("id");

console.log(id1 === id2);

Output:

false

Each Symbol is always unique.

