5. Primitive vs Reference Types
Primitive	Reference
Stored by value	Stored by reference
Immutable	Mutable
Stack	Heap
Fixed size	Dynamic size
Independent copy	Shared reference
6. JavaScript Memory Model

JavaScript mainly uses two memory areas:

Memory
   |
   +---- Stack Memory
   |
   +---- Heap Memory
7. Stack Memory

Stack stores:

Primitive values
Function calls
Execution contexts
References to objects

Example:

let a = 10;
let b = a;

Memory:

STACK

a ----> 10
b ----> 10

Changing one doesn't affect the other.

b = 20;

console.log(a); //10
console.log(b); //20
8. Heap Memory

Heap stores:

Objects
Arrays
Functions

Example:

let obj = {
    name: "Piyush"
};

Memory:

STACK                HEAP

obj ----------->   {
                     name:"Piyush"
                   }
9. Copying Primitive Values
let x = 10;
let y = x;

y = 20;

Memory:

STACK

x ---> 10
y ---> 20

Output:

10
20
10. Copying Objects
let a = {
    name:"Piyush"
};

let b = a;

Memory:

STACK              HEAP

a -----------+
             |
b -----------+----> {
                     name:"Piyush"
                   }

Now:

b.name = "Raj";

console.log(a.name);

Output:

Raj

Because both variables point to the same object.

11. Shallow Copy
let obj1 = {
    name:"Piyush"
};

let obj2 = {...obj1};

Memory:

obj1 ---> Object1
obj2 ---> Object2

Top-level properties are copied.

Problem with Nested Objects
let obj1 = {
    name:"Piyush",
    address:{
        city:"Jaipur"
    }
};

let obj2 = {...obj1};

obj2.address.city = "Delhi";

Result:

console.log(obj1.address.city);

Output:

Delhi

Because nested objects still share references.

