15. Call Stack

JavaScript is single-threaded.

Example:

function one(){
    two();
}

function two(){
    three();
}

function three(){
    console.log("Hello");
}

one();

Call stack:

Global
one()
two()
three()

Then:

Global
16. Garbage Collection

JavaScript automatically manages memory.

It uses the Mark-and-Sweep Algorithm.

Example:

let obj = {
    name:"Piyush"
};

obj = null;

Now no variable references that object.

Object becomes unreachable
        ↓
Garbage Collector removes it
17. Memory Leak

Occurs when objects remain referenced unnecessarily.

Example:

let cache = [];

function add(){
    cache.push(new Array(1000000));
}

Calling repeatedly:

add();
add();
add();

Memory keeps increasing.

18. Pass By Value vs Pass By Reference

Many students say:

JavaScript uses pass by value for primitives and pass by reference for objects.

This is not technically correct.

JavaScript always uses pass by value.

For objects, the value being passed is the reference itself.

Example:

let obj = {
    age:20
};

function test(x){
    x.age = 30;
}

test(obj);

console.log(obj.age);

Output:

30

Because the copied value is the object's reference.

